{"id":"1909.12690","submitter":"Akbar Ali","authors":"Akbar Ali, Gary Chartrand, James Hallas and Ping Zhang","title":"Extremal Problems in Royal Colorings of Graphs","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Journal of Combinatorial Mathematics and Combinatorial Computing\n  116 (2021) 201-218","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  An edge coloring $c$ of a graph $G$ is a royal $k$-edge coloring of $G$ if\nthe edges of $G$ are assigned nonempty subsets of the set $\\{1, 2, \\ldots, k\\}$\nin such a way that the vertex coloring obtained by assigning the union of the\ncolors of the incident edges of each vertex is a proper vertex coloring. If the\nvertex coloring is vertex-distinguishing, then $c$ is a strong royal $k$-edge\ncoloring. The minimum positive integer $k$ for which $G$ has a strong royal\n$k$-edge coloring is the strong royal index of $G$. It has been conjectured\nthat if $G$ is a connected graph of order $n\\ge 4$ where $2^{k-1} \\le n \\le\n2^k-1$ for a positive integer $k$, then the strong royal index of $G$ is either\n$k$ or $k+1$. We discuss this conjecture along with other information\nconcerning strong royal colorings of graphs. A sufficient condition for such a\ngraph to have a strong royal index $k+1$ is presented.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 27 Sep 2019 13:51:43 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-08-16"}
